substitute decision-maker is required","Withdrawal can only occur if previously documented","Withdrawal constitutes assisted dying","Court approval must be obtained before withdrawal","Withdrawal requires unanimous agreement from all family members"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct principle is that \u003Cstrong\u003Evalid consent from substitute decision-maker is required\u003C/strong\u003E for withdrawal of life-sustaining treatment. When a patient lacks capacity, their substitute decision-maker can provide valid consent based on the patient\u0027s known wishes or best interests.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe hierarchy of substitute decision-makers (in order) is:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EAppointed guardian (by tribunal)\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EEnduring guardian (appointed by patient while competent)\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003ESpouse or domestic partner (including de facto)\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EPrimary carer\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EClose friend or relative\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options are not valid because:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E            \u003Cli\u003EWhile advance care documentation is helpful, \u003Cstrong\u003Ewithdrawal can only occur if previously documented\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as valid substitute decision-maker consent is sufficient\u003C/li\u003E            \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithdrawal constitutes assisted dying\u003C/strong\u003E mischaracterises the nature of treatment withdrawal, which is a distinct and accepted medical practice\u003C/li\u003E            \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECourt approval must be obtained before withdrawal\u003C/strong\u003E overstates legal requirements - courts are only involved in disputed cases\u003C/li\u003E            \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithdrawal requires unanimous agreement from all family members\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly suggests all relatives must agree rather than just the designated decision-maker\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe principle of double effect recognises that providing appropriate palliative care during withdrawal, even if it may hasten death, is ethically acceptable when the primary intention is relief of suffering rather than causing death.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Withdrawal of life-sustaining treatment requires valid consent from a competent patient or their substitute decision-maker.","The principle of double effect recognises that providing comfort care which may hasten death is ethically acceptable if the primary intention is symptom relief.","There is no ethical or legal distinction between withholding and withdrawing life-sustaining treatment.","Substitute decision-makers are determined by a clear legal hierarchy starting with appointed guardian, then enduring guardian, spouse, carer, and close friend or relative."],"references":["End of life law - withholding and withdrawing treatment. End of Life Decisions for Aged Care. Updated 2024. Available from: https://www.eldac.com.au/Our-Toolkits/End-of-Life-Law/Withholding-and-Withdrawing-Life-Sustaining-Medical-Treatment/Factsheet#:~:text=Generally%20a%20health%20professional%20must,a%20person\u0027s%20substitute%20decision%2Dmaker."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61009"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18080"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61009"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T21:55:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T21:56:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10794"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75499"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes